      "source": [
        "<h1> SCENARIO BASESD QUESTION </h1>"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "W0f936VReMr4"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "1<B>.Compare Pickle and Joblib as serialisation choices for this deployment context.\n",
        "Which would you use and why? What risks does each carry when the model is loaded back in an\n",
        "environment that differs from the one it was trained in?</B>\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "c_yWYM4BzqwC"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Answer:\n",
        "\n",
        "When deploying a scikit-learn delivery time prediction model in a Flask application, both Pickle and Joblib can serialize (save) the trained model.\n",
        "\n",
        "Pickle\n",
        "Python's built-in serialization library.\n",
        "Suitable for small Python objects.\n",
        "Simpler and universally available.\n",
        "Slower for large NumPy arrays.\n",
        "Joblib\n",
        "Specifically optimized for machine learning models.\n",
        "Efficient for storing large NumPy arrays.\n",
        "Faster loading and saving for scikit-learn models.\n",
        "Uses less memory during loading.\n",
        "Which would I choose?\n",
        "\n",
        "For this deployment, I would choose Joblib because:\n",
        "\n",
        "The model is built using scikit-learn.\n",
        "The service handles hundreds of requests per hour.\n",
        "Joblib loads models faster and is optimized for numerical data.\n",
        "Risks\n",
        "\n",
        "Pickle\n",
        "\n",
        "Unsafe if loading files from untrusted sources (can execute malicious code).\n",
        "Compatibility issues if Python or library versions change.\n",
        "\n",
        "Joblib\n",
        "\n",
        "Same security risk as Pickle.\n",
        "Model may fail to load correctly if the deployment environment has different versions of Python, scikit-learn, or NumPy.\n",
        "Conclusion\n",
        "\n",
        "Joblib is the preferred choice because it provides better performance for machine learning models while requiring the deployment environment to match the training environment."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "C3KaufKn0brC"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "2.<B>A colleague suggests using a Variational Autoencoder (VAE), while another\n",
        "recommends a Stable Diffusion-based model. Compare the two approaches for this\n",
        "image-generation task — address their key architectural differences, output quality, and which is\n",
        "more appropriate for a production marketing pipeline.</B>\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "eC7ezuTn0pE8"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Variational Autoencoder (VAE)\n",
        "Encoder compresses the image into a latent space.\n",
        "Decoder reconstructs the image.\n",
        "Fast training and inference.\n",
        "Produces smoother but often blurry images.\n",
        "Good for representation learning rather than photorealistic generation.\n",
        "Stable Diffusion\n",
        "Diffusion model that gradually removes noise to generate an image.\n",
        "Uses text conditioning and attention mechanisms.\n",
        "Produces highly realistic and detailed images.\n",
        "Supports image-to-image generation using reference images.\n",
        "Better prompt understanding.\n",
        "Comparison\n",
        "Feature\tVAE\tStable Diffusion\n",
        "Architecture\tEncoder-Decoder\tDiffusion Model\n",
        "Image Quality\tModerate, blurry\tHigh, photorealistic\n",
        "Text Understanding\tLimited\tExcellent\n",
        "Reference Image Support\tBasic\tStrong\n",
        "Marketing Use\tNot ideal\tHighly suitable\n",
        "Which is better?\n",
        "\n",
        "I would use Stable Diffusion because:\n",
        "\n",
        "Generates realistic promotional images.\n",
        "Better understands restaurant descriptions.\n",
        "Produces visually rich marketing content.\n",
        "Supports image editing and image-to-image generation."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Zlp5cZxo0sAT"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "3.<B>GPT-style decoder-only models and BERT-style encoder-only models are both\n",
        "available to your team. Which architecture is better suited to each job, and what fundamental\n",
        "property of each architecture makes it the right choice for that specific task?</b>\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "s7Ibivi80_gA"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Job 1: Answering open-ended questions\n",
        "Architecture: GPT (Decoder-only)\n",
        "Reason: GPT is designed for text generation. It uses autoregressive generation, predicting the next word based on previous words, which makes it ideal for generating natural and conversational answers.\n",
        "Job 2: Classifying customer reviews (Positive, Neutral, Negative)\n",
        "Architecture: BERT (Encoder-only)\n",
        "Reason: BERT is designed for text understanding. It uses bidirectional context, meaning it reads both the left and right context of a sentence, making it highly accurate for sentiment classification.\n",
        "\n",
        "Conclusion:\n",
        "\n",
        "GPT (Decoder-only) → Best for text generation and answering open-ended questions.\n",
        "BERT (Encoder-only) → Best for text understanding and sentiment classification because it understands the full context of the sentence."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "JBe-yFHbWgX9"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "4.<b> Explain the difference between zero-shot and few-shot prompting. Given the\n",
        "constraints described, which strategy would you apply, and how would you structure the prompt\n",
        "to maximise the quality of the bot's responses?</b>\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "RRhw17xlb8NL"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Difference between Zero-shot and Few-shot Prompting\n",
        "\n",
        "Zero-shot Prompting:\n",
        "The model is given only the instruction and no examples. It generates a response based on its pre-trained knowledge.\n",
        "Few-shot Prompting:\n",
        "The model is given the instruction along with a few example input-output pairs. These examples help the model understand the required response format and improve accuracy.\n",
        "Which Strategy Should Be Used?\n",
        "\n",
        "In this scenario, the team has 3 annotated complaint–response pairs for each category. Therefore, Few-shot Prompting is the best choice because the available examples help the model understand how to respond to complaint categories it has not been explicitly trained on.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "*Prompt Structure*\n",
        "You are a customer support assistant for a food delivery platform.\n",
        "Respond politely, apologize for the inconvenience, and provide an appropriate solution.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example 1:\n",
        "Complaint: Wrong item delivered.\n",
        "Response: We are sorry that you received the wrong item. We will arrange a replacement or refund as soon as possible.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example 2:\n",
        "Complaint: Packaging damaged.\n",
        "Response: We apologize for the damaged packaging. We will investigate the issue and offer a replacement or refund.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example 3:\n",
        "Complaint: Missing cutlery.\n",
        "Response: We are sorry that the cutlery was missing. We will notify the restaurant and ensure better service in the future.\n",
        "\n",
        "Now respond to this complaint:\n",
        "Complaint: [User Complaint]\n",
        "Response:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Few-shot prompting is the most suitable strategy because the available 3 complaint–response examples guide the model to produce accurate, consistent, and customer-friendly responses, even for complaint categories it has not been explicitly trained on."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Fv4IdliIb62r"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "5.<b>Describe what distinguishes a LangChain agent from a simple LLM chain. Given that\n",
        "your food ordering assistant must check live restaurant availability, call an API to calculate\n",
        "estimated delivery time, and validate discount codes, justify which approach is more\n",
        "appropriate — and identify two risks the agent approach introduces.</b>\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "QBmlH42mdWkx"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Difference between a LangChain Agent and a Simple LLM Chain\n",
        "Simple LLM Chain:\n",
        "Executes a fixed sequence of steps.\n",
        "Takes the user's input and generates a response directly.\n",
        "Cannot decide which external tool or API to use.\n",
        "Best for simple question-answering and text generation tasks.\n",
        "LangChain Agent:\n",
        "Can reason and make decisions.\n",
        "Dynamically selects and uses multiple tools or APIs based on the user's request.\n",
        "Can perform multi-step tasks before generating the final response.\n",
        "Best for complex workflows requiring external data.\n",
        "Which Approach is More Appropriate?\n",
        "\n",
        "For the food ordering assistant, the LangChain Agent is the better choice because it needs to:\n",
        "\n",
        "Check live restaurant availability.\n",
        "Call an API to calculate the estimated delivery time.\n",
        "Validate discount codes.\n",
        "Combine the results from these tools to generate the final response.\n",
        "\n",
        "A simple LLMChain cannot reliably perform these real-time actions because it only generates text and does not dynamically interact with external tools.\n",
        "\n",
        "Two Risks of Using a LangChain Agent\n",
        "Higher Complexity\n",
        "Agents require multiple tools, APIs, and reasoning steps, making them more difficult to develop, test, and maintain.\n",
        "Slower Response & Higher Cost\n",
        "Since the agent may perform several API calls and multiple LLM reasoning steps, it increases response time and API usage cost.\n",
        "Conclusion\n",
        "\n",
        "A LangChain Agent is the most suitable approach because it can use external tools, access live data, and make decisions during execution. Although it introduces higher complexity and increased latency/cost, it is the best solution for a food ordering assistant that relies on real-time restaurant availability, delivery estimation, and discount validation."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2RQ0DJ_BdnGb"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "6.<b>Compare fine-tuning and RAG for this specific scenario. Address update frequency,\n",
        "cost, hallucination risk, and data privacy. Which approach is more suitable for a daily-updated,\n",
        "document-grounded Q&A bot, and what limitations does your recommended approach still\n",
        "carry?</b>\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Y8As4vzTdsCm"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "For this food delivery chatbot, RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) is more suitable than fine-tuning.\n",
        "\n",
        "Comparison:\n",
        "\n",
        "Update Frequency: Fine-tuning requires retraining the model whenever the 500-page policy or daily menu changes. RAG only requires updating the document database, so changes are reflected immediately.\n",
        "Cost: Fine-tuning is expensive because it requires repeated model training. RAG is more cost-effective since only the knowledge base needs to be updated.\n",
        "Hallucination Risk: Fine-tuning may generate outdated or incorrect information. RAG reduces hallucinations by retrieving relevant information from the latest documents before generating the answer.\n",
        "Data Privacy: In fine-tuning, sensitive information may become part of the trained model. In RAG, documents remain in a secure database and are retrieved only when needed, providing better data privacy.\n",
        "\n",
        "Recommended Approach:\n",
        "RAG is the best choice because the chatbot must answer questions from a 500-page policy document and a daily updated menu catalogue. It provides accurate, up-to-date, document-based responses without retraining the model every day.\n",
        "\n",
        "Limitations of RAG:\n",
        "\n",
        "If the retrieval system fails to find the correct document, the chatbot may give incomplete or incorrect answers.\n",
        "RAG is more complex to implement because it requires embeddings, a vector database, and a retrieval pipeline.\n",
        "\n",
        "For a daily-updated, document-grounded Q&A chatbot, RAG is the most suitable approach because it is cheaper, easier to update, more accurate, reduces hallucinations, and provides better data privacy than fine-tuning."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "sg2SGv9NdypD"
      }
    },
